---
description: Rules for backend agent files — classes that orchestrate an LLM call with a prompt.
globs: "backend/app/agents/**/*.py"
alwaysApply: false
---

## What is an agent

An agent is a class whose primary responsibility is to call LLMService with a
prompt it owns. If a class calls LLMService, it is an agent — name it and place
it accordingly. If a class does not call LLMService, it is a service — keep it
in `backend/app/services/`.

Current agents:

- `drift_agent.py` — detects whether a Work Order is stale after a section save
- `conflict_agent.py` — finds conflicts and gaps between section pairs
- `work_order_agent.py` — generates Work Orders from selected sections
- `section_relationship_agent.py` — detects relationships between sections on publish
- `software_chat_agent.py` — software-scoped chat streaming
- `project_chat_agent.py` — project-scoped chat streaming (system prompt + RAG text)
- `citation_health_agent.py` — structured citation coverage for a section
- `builder_composer_agent.py` — builder home composer hint strings
- `section_improve_agent.py` — revises section markdown from RAG + instruction

---

## File structure — non-negotiable

Every agent file must follow this exact top-to-bottom layout:

```python
# ── Prompts ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

SYSTEM_PROMPT = """..."""

USER_PROMPT = """..."""

# ── Schemas ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# (Include this section only when the agent uses LLMService.chat_structured.)
THING_JSON_SCHEMA: dict[str, Any] = {
    "name": "thing",
    "strict": True,
    "schema": {
        "type": "object",
        ...
    },
}


# ── Agent ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

class XxxAgent:
    ...
```

Rules:

- Prompts are module-level constants, above the class, under the `# ── Prompts` section comment.
- Use SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE: `SYSTEM_PROMPT`, `USER_PROMPT`. If a file needs more
  than one user prompt, be specific: `ANALYSIS_PROMPT`, `SUMMARY_PROMPT`.
- Never define prompt strings inside methods or as class attributes.
- Prompts must be written in English only.
- For `chat_stream`-only agents, `USER_PROMPT` may be an empty string (user turns are in `messages`).
- Structured agents may use `USER_PROMPT` as a format template (e.g. contains `{placeholder}`) when the final string is built with `.format(...)`.
- **Structured JSON (`chat_structured`):** The OpenAI-style envelope passed as `json_schema` (`name`, `strict: True`, inner `schema` object) must be a module-level constant in **this same file**, under `# ── Schemas ──`, placed **after** the prompts block and **before** the agent class. Name it clearly (e.g. `WORK_ORDER_BATCH_JSON_SCHEMA`, `CONFLICT_ANALYSIS_SCHEMA`). Do **not** define response schemas in `llm_service.py` or in orchestrating services — only `LLMService.chat_structured()` validates and forwards what the agent supplies.
---

## Naming

- Class name ends in `Agent`: `DriftAgent`, `ConflictAgent`, `WorkOrderAgent`.
- File name ends in `_agent.py`: `drift_agent.py`.

---

## Dependencies

- Agents receive `LLMService` (and usually `AsyncSession`) via constructor injection.
- Orchestrating services may import agents to delegate LLM calls; agents must not import those services back (avoid cycles).
- Agents may use SQLAlchemy models with an injected `AsyncSession` when they load or persist domain data as part of the same flow.

---

## LLM calls

- Always use `LLMService.chat_structured()` for structured output (JSON schema required).
- Always use `LLMService.chat_stream()` for streaming user-facing responses.
- Never call an LLM provider SDK directly.
- Always pass `call_type` so TokenTracker records it correctly.
- Always use `LLMService.chat_structured()` for structured output (JSON schema required); the schema dict lives in this agent file (see **File structure** and structured-json rule under Prompts).
---

## Prompt content

- All prompt strings must be written in English only.
- Prompts must be extracted verbatim from their origin — do not paraphrase or
  restructure during a refactor. Behaviour changes require a separate PR.
- Each agent owns its prompts. Do not share prompt constants across agents.

---

## Tests

- Unit test file: `backend/tests/unit/agents/test_<name>_agent.py`
- Mock `LLMService` deterministically — never make real LLM calls in unit tests.
- LLM integration test: `backend/tests/llm/test_<name>_agent.py` with `@pytest.mark.llm`.
- Renaming a service to an agent requires renaming its test files accordingly.
